<p>Joanne Ooi, Samantha Woods, Paul Zimmerman and Nissa Marion are four people with different backgrounds, but a common goal: to make Hong Kong a more pleasant and cleaner place to live. </p>

<p>It was Ooi’s children that woke her up to the issue of air pollution: “It was causing my young son to have a chronic cough,” she says. Ooi has a marketing background and is the founder of jewellery boutique Plukka, but became acquainted with the topic after attending a conference in 2008 titled The Air We Breathe. “I wanted to bring in my knowledge of consumer branding, package it and activate the public,” says Ooi. She became CEO of Clean Air Network, a non-governmental organisation founded in 2008, of which she is now a director. </p>

<p>Making the city more pedestrian friendly and limiting the pollution caused by motor vehicle, especially heavily polluting diesel commercial vehicles, is high on her list of priorities.  </p>

<p>Woods is a co-founder at Time to Grow, an organisation set up to promote urban farming. Her inspiration came from a group of university students she met in Beijing who were growing vegetables. Back in Hong Kong, she formed Time to Grow with two partners. </p>

<p>“I think people in Hong Kong have always been conscious of eating healthy and chemical-free foods,” she says, “but one of the first mindsets we needed to change was this idea that there’s not enough space for this.” In reality, she says, there are suitable empty spaces across the city, from rooftops and balconies to small plots of land. </p>

<p>Zimmerman is a Southern District Councillor representing Pok Fu Lam, Advisor to the Society for Protection of the Harbour, and Secretary for the Community for Road Safety, but one of his most prominent positions is CEO of Designing Hong Kong, a non-governmental organisation advocating sustainable urban planning and development.  </p>

<p>“It’s about enjoyment of public space,” he says. “Public space does not mean parks. It’s the street. It’s the pavement. The focus today is really on walkability, access to the water, and how we safeguard our ecological habitats.”  </p>

<p>On a sunny autumn day in 2003, Nissa Marion was shocked to arrive at Tai Long Wan beach in Sai Kung. “I was dismayed by the amount of trash,” she says. This prompted her to become active in environmental issues; she came to be active in Hong Kong Cleanup, an annual event that brings together volunteers to clear beaches and country parks of litter and raise awareness of the city’s waste crisis.  </p>

<p>“When we first started doing clean-ups in 2000, we had about 40 people. Last year, we had over 50,000 volunteers,” Marion says. Hong Kong Cleanup also has broader educational value. “The easiest thing an individual can do is reduce plastic waste. My favourite message is: reduce your disposables.”  </p>

